2026-07-08T23:25:49Z UTC
Change: Merged the standalone Products-management page into the Stock page (frontend-only; no backend/migration changes). User reported after the big physical reorg that "the product page and stock page have almost the same function" -- investigation confirmed this was a real bug, not just visual redundancy: pages/products/ProductRevenuePage.tsx's per-row "edit products" table let a user type a new availableQuantity directly, which PATCHes products via products::repository::update -- a raw `UPDATE products SET available_quantity = $14 ...` with no row lock, no stock_policy enforcement, no stock_movements ledger row, and no audit_logs entry. Meanwhile pages/stock/StockPage.tsx's record-movement form goes through modules/stock/repository.rs::create, which locks the product row, recomputes the quantity from a delta, enforces block_when_empty, writes the ledger row, and writes an audit log entry. So editing a product's quantity on the Products page silently overwrote whatever the Stock ledger said, with zero record of why -- a real audit-trail integrity gap, not a cosmetic duplication.
Requested behavior: user chose "merge the both pages and make the products to be managed through the stock page" when asked how to reconcile the two paths (via AskUserQuestion, after I'd already presented three narrower options -- the user's answer was a fourth option I hadn't offered, so I designed the merge from scratch rather than picking from my own menu).
Design: mbam-web/src/pages/stock/StockPage.tsx now hosts both the product catalog (search/sort, add-products + CSV import, per-row edit, revenue/best-selling columns -- moved verbatim from ProductRevenuePage.tsx) and the existing stock ledger + record-movement form. The one deliberate behavior change: the per-row "availableQuantity" cell is now ALWAYS read-only (the inventory-snapshot badge that used to only show outside edit mode), even while isEditingProducts is true -- the record-movement form below is now the only UI path that changes quantity, closing the audit-trail gap. Everything else (name/sku/brand/category/expiryDate/costPrice/businessUnitId/stockPolicy edits, CSV import, bulk add) is unchanged. ProductDraft.availableQuantity is still tracked and still sent back in the update payload (via draftPayload/rowPayload) even though the UI never lets it change -- products::repository::update has no partial-update semantics (binds whatever the payload says as a positional param), so omitting the field or sending null would NULL out available_quantity server-side (which the stock module's create() interprets as "this product doesn't track quantity" -- see its `let Some(current) = available_quantity else { return Err(...) }` guard). New products (via the bulk add-products grid and CSV import) can still set an initial quantity at creation time, since there's no existing ledger to contradict yet -- I initially removed this too by mistake (over-applying the fix) and restored it before finishing.
Permission-model note: the merged page is gated by ProtectedRoute at /stock, whose routeKey requires screen.stock or stock.movement.create. But the role-cashier baseline has screen.products (and product.create/update) and NOT screen.stock or any stock.movement.* permission (confirmed via mbam-api/src/dev/demo_data.rs's role permission arrays and accessControl.ts's routeAccessByRole) -- moving product management under a stock-only gate would have silently locked cashiers out of a capability they have today. Fixed by adding an `altRouteKey` prop to routing/ProtectedRoute.tsx so a route can unlock on either of two permissions; /stock now uses `routeKey="stock" altRouteKey="products"`. Inside StockPage.tsx, `canViewProductsSection = canViewDashboardMetric(member, "products")` gates the whole product-catalog section independently of `canViewLedger`/`canCreateMovement`, so a stock-only member still sees just the ledger/form (as before) and a products-only member still sees just the catalog (as before) -- no existing access was widened or narrowed, only the URL and the file that renders it changed.
Routing/nav changes: AppRoutes.tsx -- removed the ProductRevenuePage import and its `/products/manage` route entirely; that path now `<Navigate to="/stock" replace />` (kept as a redirect rather than a 404 in case it's bookmarked). ScopedEntityReportPage.tsx's "Manage products" link now points to `/stock` instead of `/products/manage`. The separate `/products` (ScopedEntityReportPage, a read-only report) and `/products/:entityId` routes are untouched -- the user's request was specifically about the two pages that both mutated stock quantity, not the reporting views.
Files changed: mbam-web/src/pages/stock/StockPage.tsx (rewritten, ~2x size), mbam-web/src/pages/stock/StockPage.css (ProductRevenuePage.css's rules appended verbatim in a clearly-labeled block), mbam-web/src/routing/ProtectedRoute.tsx (+altRouteKey), mbam-web/src/routing/AppRoutes.tsx, mbam-web/src/pages/reports/ScopedEntityReportPage.tsx (one link href). Deleted: mbam-web/src/pages/products/ProductRevenuePage.tsx, mbam-web/src/pages/products/ProductRevenuePage.css (folder removed once empty). Also de-exported StockPolicyOption/STOCK_POLICY_OPTIONS (were `export`ed from ProductRevenuePage.tsx with zero external importers -- confirmed via grep before and after) since keeping them exported from the merged file triggered a new react-refresh/only-export-components eslint warning that didn't exist as a *failure* before only because nothing had run `eslint --max-warnings 0` against this exact combination; reproduced the same warning against the original file's unmodified content standalone to confirm it predates this change and isn't a regression I introduced by merging.
Debugging and verification performed: `npx tsc --noEmit` clean. `npx eslint src --ext .ts,.tsx --max-warnings 0` clean (after the de-export fix above). `npx vitest run` -- 77/77 tests passing across 23 files, same counts as before this change (no test file existed for ProductRevenuePage.tsx, and grep confirmed no other test references it or the deleted path, so nothing needed updating/deleting on the test side). `npx vite build --mode production` succeeds (chunk-size-limit warning is pre-existing/unrelated). Grepped the whole frontend src tree for "ProductRevenuePage" and "pages/products" post-deletion -- zero remaining references outside StockPage.tsx's own explanatory comments. REPOSITORY_MAP.md's `pages/products/` row rewritten into the `pages/stock/` row to describe the merge.
Checks not run: live browser verification against the user's actual dev server -- attempted via Claude in Chrome against http://localhost:5173/ but the dev server was not reachable from that session (page showed a browser error page, no console/page content available). Asked the user whether their `npm run dev` was running and on what port; this response is pending, so the merge has NOT yet been visually confirmed working in a real browser. This should be done as the very next step once the user replies.
Remaining risks and follow-up: (1) The concurrent-edit staleness window on ProductDraft.availableQuantity (recording a stock movement while a product-edit is mid-flight, then saving the product edit, could clobber the fresh quantity with the stale snapshot captured when editing started) is a pre-existing risk inherited unchanged from the original ProductRevenuePage -- not introduced or worsened by this change, but also not fixed; a real fix would need the backend to support partial updates (e.g. NULLable/optional columns treated as "leave unchanged" via COALESCE) rather than a full-replace PATCH. (2) No automated test directly exercises the merged page's two-section gating (canViewProductsSection vs canViewLedger vs canCreateMovement all independently true/false) -- existing coverage was 0 dedicated tests for either original page, so this isn't a regression, but it's a gap worth closing given the page just doubled in responsibility. (3) cargo build/test still cannot be run in this sandbox (no Rust toolchain) -- moot for this specific change since it touched zero backend files, but flagging per standing practice.

2026-07-08T16:55:49Z UTC
Change: Built the backend foundation for stock management -- a manual stock-movement ledger module, sale-driven automatic stock deduction, and a settable per-product stock policy -- per the user's request to "move to our stock management solution" after reviewing docs/future-stock-management.md, and choosing "Backend ledger + sale deduction" as the starting phase from a menu of options I presented.
Key design decision: products are already 1:1 with a business_unit_id (0008_product_unit_scope.sql), so no separate multi-location "stock profile" table was needed as future-stock-management.md originally assumed -- available_quantity already lives on the product row that belongs to exactly one shop. This significantly simplified the implementation versus the original plan.
Migration (mbam-api/migrations/0013_stock_movements.sql): new `stock_movements` append-only ledger table (product_id, business_account/business/business_unit ids, movement_type, quantity_delta, unit_cost, source_transaction_id, source_receipt_import_id, note, created_by, created_at), a new `products.stock_policy` column (allow_negative/warn_when_low/block_when_empty, default warn_when_low), and two new permissions `stock.movement.create`/`stock.movement.view` (granted to existing master_owner roles explicitly, matching the 0009_screen_permissions.sql pattern; business_admin/shop_manager get them via team/repository.rs's standard_roles() self-healing the next time ensure_standard_roles runs; cashier intentionally excluded).
New backend module (mbam-api/src/modules/stock/): model.rs (StockMovement, StockMovementWriteRequest), repository.rs (find_product_scope for pre-lock scope resolution, create() which locks the product row FOR UPDATE, checks idempotency by movement id *after* acquiring that lock so a truly concurrent retry serializes behind it instead of racing it, enforces block_when_empty, and rejects movements against untracked (available_quantity IS NULL) products outright rather than silently writing a no-op ledger row), service.rs (validate() extracted as a pure/testable function; "sale" is rejected as a manual movement type -- it may only ever be written by transactions::repository), routes.rs (POST/GET /api/v1/stock/movements, mounted at /api/v1/stock). Manual movement types: opening_balance, purchase, sale_refund, manual_adjustment, transfer_in, transfer_out, damaged, expired, returned.
Sale-driven deduction (mbam-api/src/modules/transactions/repository.rs): new apply_sale_stock_deductions, called from inside create()'s existing `existing_lines` idempotency guard (so a retried offline-sync push can never double-deduct), sums quantity per product_id across all lines, locks each product row FOR UPDATE in sorted (BTreeMap) order to avoid lock-ordering deadlocks, skips untracked products silently (unlike the manual path, since a sale isn't the user explicitly asking for an inventory event), and enforces block_when_empty by rejecting the whole transaction (whole DB transaction rolls back via Transaction::drop, since repository::create's return type changed from Result<_, sqlx::Error> to Result<_, ApiError> to allow returning a business-level BadRequest from inside this new code path).
Products API (mbam-api/src/modules/products/{model,service,repository}.rs): exposed the new stock_policy column through ProductWriteRequest/Product (it would otherwise have been an orphaned DB column unreachable from the API); validated against the three allowed values.
Sync wiring (mbam-api/src/modules/sync/service.rs): new "stock_movement" entityType branch in apply_operation/apply_stock_movement_operation, reusing the offline-generated id as the server id (same idempotency trick transactions already use) so the stockLocalRepository.ts queue built earlier this session can actually sync manual movements; added a visible_stock_movements CTE + UNION branch to build_snapshot's pull query, gated on stock.movement.view, so devices see the ledger.
Test-fixture fixes (mbam-api/src/dev_seed.rs): discovered dev_seed.rs has its OWN independent permission lists (MASTER_PERMISSIONS/BUSINESS_ADMIN_PERMISSIONS/SHOP_MANAGER_PERMISSIONS/CASHIER_PERMISSIONS) separate from team/repository.rs's standard_roles() -- added the two new permissions to the first three. Also fixed a real test-pollution bug my own change would have introduced: upsert_product's ON CONFLICT clause never reset available_quantity, so the existing manager_scope_tests_cover_shop_resources_and_report_denials test (which records one real sale against PRODUCT_ONE_ID via the HTTP API) would have permanently drained that seeded product's quantity by 1 on every single test run, forever, once sale-driven deduction shipped. Fixed by resetting available_quantity/low_stock_threshold/stock_policy on every reseed.
New integration tests (mbam-api/src/checklist_tests.rs): stock_movement_endpoints_are_role_gated_and_scoped (cashier denied, shop_manager scoped-in succeeds, shop_manager denied for a product outside their unit, manual "sale" rejected with 400, list scoped correctly, audit logged) and sale_creation_deducts_stock_and_blocks_when_policy_requires_it (a normal sale deducts stock and writes a movement row; a second sale exceeding remaining block_when_empty stock is rejected with 400 and leaves the product quantity, movement count, and transaction list completely unchanged, proving the whole DB transaction rolled back rather than partially applying).
Requested behavior: user asked for "ideas on how to implement and integrate" stock management; after I presented a phased plan (ideas only / low-stock badges only / manual movements / backend ledger + sale deduction), user picked "Backend ledger + sale deduction" as the starting phase via AskUserQuestion.
Debugging and verification performed: No Rust toolchain available in this sandbox (see prior sessions), so `cargo check`/`cargo build`/`cargo test` could not be run directly. Read every new and modified file in full myself, then spawned an independent read-only review agent (fresh context, no access to my reasoning) to re-check bind-count/placeholder-order correctness across every new/modified SQL query, query_as tuple-to-column matching, borrow-checker correctness of the &mut Transaction helper function, error-type propagation through the changed transactions::repository::create signature, struct-literal completeness for ProductWriteRequest/Product, JSON field-name and query-string-parameter-name correctness in the new integration tests, and FK-safe test-fixture cleanup ordering. That review found no compile errors, but did find one real logic bug (a manual stock movement against an untracked product silently wrote a ledger row with no matching quantity change) which I fixed -- see repository.rs's `let Some(current) = available_quantity else { return Err(...) }` guard.
Errors encountered: The independent review's one real finding (untracked-product manual movements silently no-op'ing instead of being rejected) was fixed before this commit. A second, lower-severity finding (products::repository::update resets stock_policy to the default if the caller's payload omits it, since update() is a full-replace endpoint) was NOT fixed -- it's a carry-over of the pre-existing full-replace contract already applied to every other optional product field (category, default_price, etc.), not a new pattern introduced by this change, and fixing it would mean redesigning update() semantics for all fields, out of scope for this phase.
Checks not run: cargo check/build/test -- STRONGLY recommend the user run `cargo test` locally before merging, especially the two new checklist_tests.rs integration tests and the existing manager_scope_tests_cover_shop_resources_and_report_denials test (to confirm the dev_seed.rs fix actually prevents the quantity-drift regression). No live-browser/manual verification of any endpoint (no UI consumes this yet -- deliberately backend-only per the chosen phase).
Remaining risks and follow-up: (1) products::repository::update's full-replace semantics mean editing a product via the current UI (once one exists) without resending stockPolicy will silently reset it -- harmless today since no UI sets stockPolicy yet, but worth fixing before any product-edit UI exposes this field. (2) block_when_empty enforcement on the sale path is a real behavior change (a sale can now be rejected outright) -- currently only reachable if a business_admin/shop_manager explicitly sets stockPolicy via a raw API call, since no UI exposes it yet, so the blast radius is naturally contained for now. (3) No UI exists at all yet (ledger view, record-movement form, low-stock badge) -- natural next phase. (4) Conflict handling for two devices concurrently recording manual movements on the same product relies on a DB row lock (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE), not a merge strategy -- fine at current expected scale, revisit if it becomes a bottleneck.

