2026-07-01T20:32:08Z UTC
Change: Root-caused and permanently fixed the recurring "stuck .git/*.lock" issue that had been blocking local git writes against this mounted repo folder all session, previously worked around by cloning into the sandbox's native filesystem and pushing from there.
Implementation: Confirmed via direct testing that the mounted folder's FUSE bridge blocks `unlink()` (file deletion) mount-wide by default, not just for `.git` internals — git's own lock-then-rename-then-delete-temp-file workflow (`index.lock`, `packed-refs.lock`, loose-object `tmp_obj_*` files) depends on deleting those transient files, so any write operation that left one behind became permanently stuck. Called the Cowork `allow_cowork_file_delete` tool once for a file inside this folder, which enabled deletion for the entire `mbam` folder going forward (not just the single requested path). Removed the two stuck lock files, ran `git reset --hard godwillacho/main` directly against the mounted repo (previously impossible), and cleaned up orphaned untracked files left over from the reverted Plasmic integration. The local checkout is now fully synced to `main` with a clean `git status`.
Verification: `git status --short` empty; `git log --oneline -3` matches GitHub's `main` HEAD (`d4b83d9`); `rm` on a fresh test file inside the mount succeeded after the fix, confirming deletion is durably enabled (not a one-time grant).
Checks not run: none; this is an infrastructure/tooling fix with no application code touched.

2026-07-02T15:01:37Z UTC
Change: Investigated and resolved GitHub Dependabot alert #2 (jsonwebtoken Type Confusion, CVE-2026-25537, GHSA-h395-gr6q-cpjc) flagged on `mbam-api/Cargo.lock` after the previous push.
Investigation: The advisory describes a bypass where a malformed (wrong-JSON-type) `nbf`/`exp` claim is silently treated as absent when `validate_nbf`/`validate_exp` is enabled but the claim isn't in `required_spec_claims`. Audited every `jsonwebtoken` call site in `mbam-api/src/security/tokens.rs` (the only file using the crate): `Validation::default()` is used untouched (no `validate_nbf`/`validate_exp`/`required_spec_claims` ever set anywhere in the repo), the only decoded struct (`AccessTokenClaims`) has no `nbf` field, and `OfflineGrantClaims` is only ever encoded, never decoded, by this crate. Keycloak tokens are validated exclusively via remote introspection in `authentication/keycloak.rs`, which never imports `jsonwebtoken`. Conclusion: not exploitable in this codebase today, but upgrading is still correct hygiene.
Implementation: Since no Rust toolchain is available in this sandbox to safely hand-edit `Cargo.lock` (checksums, transitive dependency resolution) or compile-verify a major version bump, used GitHub's own "Create Dependabot security update" action on the alert to generate PR #12 (`Bump jsonwebtoken from 9.3.1 to 10.3.0`), which produced a minimal, mechanical diff (`Cargo.toml`/`Cargo.lock` only, no source changes needed — v9→v10's public API used here is unchanged).
Verification: Waited for the PR's own `Mbam API Cargo Check` GitHub Action (real Rust toolchain, `cargo check`) plus the repo's security/secret-scan checks — all 9 checks passed, no merge conflicts. Merged PR #12 (commit `21c1a96`) via the GitHub UI, which auto-deleted the Dependabot branch. Synced the local mounted repo with `git fetch` + `git reset --hard` (clean, no lock issues per the fix above).
Checks not run: No local `cargo test`/`cargo clippy` (no Rust toolchain in this sandbox); there is no existing unit/integration test exercising `create_offline_grant`'s ES256 signing path, so a runtime behavior change in that path (unlikely given the crate's public API didn't change) would not be caught by CI's `cargo check` alone. Flagging as a follow-up: consider adding a regression test for `create_offline_grant`/`verify_access_token` round-tripping.

