Change: Fixed a real bug the user reported after the styling fix above: "the save transaction button and print button are not clickable on my dashboard" (Record Transaction page, greyed out). Also did the broader app-wide `.primary-btn`/`.secondary-btn` styling pass they'd approved as a follow-up to the previous change.
Investigation: `canRecord = Object.keys(validateForm()).length === 0` was used to `disabled={formStatus === "saving" || !canRecord}` on both the "Record sale" and "Print invoice" buttons. `validateForm()` recomputes fresh on every render and requires every field (customer name, valid amount, etc.) to already be filled in and valid, so `canRecord` is `false` from the very first render before the user types anything. Because a disabled `<button>` never fires a click event, `handleSubmit` — which is what calls `setErrors(nextErrors)` to populate the page's own `validation-summary` panel — could never run. Result: both buttons were stuck looking (and being) disabled with zero feedback about what was missing, a dead end that existed before this session but was only clearly visible once the previous change gave disabled buttons a real, obviously-greyed-out look instead of blending into the page as plain unstyled browser buttons.
Implementation: Removed `!canRecord` from both buttons' `disabled` prop (kept only `formStatus === "saving"`, to still prevent a double-submit while a request is in flight) and deleted the now-unused `canRecord` variable. Clicking either button now always runs `handleSubmit`'s existing `validateForm()`/`setErrors()` flow, which either shows the specific field errors in the already-built `validation-summary` alert or proceeds with the save (and print, for that button), exactly matching how the page's own error UI was designed to work. Separately, did the approved broader styling pass: added a global base `.primary-btn`/`.secondary-btn` rule to `AppShell.css` (the root layout stylesheet loaded on every route) covering padding, border-radius, colors, icon sizing, hover/active/disabled states — the same look the Record page got, now app-wide. Removed the now-duplicate `.form-action-btn`/`.form-actions .secondary-btn` rules from `TransactionRecordPage.css` (kept the `.form-actions` flex-row layout, which is genuinely page-specific) and dropped `.print-invoice-btn` entirely since its color was identical to the new global `.primary-btn` default. Converted `.record-sale-btn` to a compound `.primary-btn.record-sale-btn` selector so its green color deterministically wins over the new global default regardless of CSS bundling order (two classes beats one on specificity, rather than relying on which stylesheet the bundler concatenates last). Audited every other file using `.primary-btn`/`.secondary-btn` (7 files: `ReportDetailTable.tsx`'s `PrintButton`, `TeamAccessPage.tsx`, `ProductRevenuePage.tsx`, `CsvImportPanel.tsx`, `TransactionDraftsPage.tsx`, `BusinessStructurePage.tsx`, `EntityReportDetailPage.tsx`) for any other single-class color override that could now collide with the new global colors on equal specificity; found exactly one (`TeamAccessPage.tsx`'s `.secondary-btn.danger-text` "disable employee" button) and fixed it the same way, converting its CSS selector from plain `.danger-text` to `.secondary-btn.danger-text`.
Files changed: `mbam-web/src/pages/transactions/TransactionRecordPage.tsx`, `TransactionRecordPage.css`; `mbam-web/src/components/app/AppShell.css`; `mbam-web/src/pages/team/TeamAccessPage.css`; `debug.log`, `docs/ENGINEERING_DEBUG_LOG.md`.
Verification: `npx tsc --noEmit` clean; `npx eslint` clean on the changed `.tsx` file; `npx vitest run` passed (21 files / 58 tests, unchanged); `npm run build` succeeded. Grepped the compiled `dist` CSS to confirm both compound selectors (`.primary-btn.record-sale-btn`, `.secondary-btn.danger-text`) actually compiled through with their intended colors, rather than assuming from source alone. Rendered a second static HTML mockup (via the visualization tool) previewing buttons/links from three of the other affected pages (Team Access, Transaction Drafts' router `<Link>`s, Reports' `PrintButton`) to sanity-check the app-wide pass before considering it done.
Errors encountered: The reported bug itself (see Investigation above) — a pre-existing logic issue this session's earlier styling change made visible, not a regression introduced by that change. Root cause and fix as described above.
Checks not run: No live browser verification (no Docker/Postgres/Keycloak stack in this sandbox) — verified by code reading, compiled-CSS inspection, and static mockups rather than the real running app.
Remaining risks: None identified for the files this session touched. The broader pass covered every current usage of `.primary-btn`/`.secondary-btn` found via `grep`, but any future page that introduces its own single-class color override on top of these two base classes should use a compound selector (`.primary-btn.foo`/`.secondary-btn.foo`) rather than a bare `.foo`, to stay safely ahead of CSS specificity/order ties — noted here so the next change follows the same pattern rather than rediscovering it.

