Investigation: Read `mbam-web/src/security/accessControl.ts`'s `canAccessRoute` closely: it checks `member.authorizedRouteKeys` FIRST (short-circuiting) and only falls back to raw `permissions` if that field is absent. `authorizedRouteKeys` is populated from the backend's `authorized_routes` field in the `/api/v1/me/authorization` response (see `services/authorizationService.ts`'s `authorized_route_keys: bootstrap.authorized_routes.map((route) => route.key)`), which is a value computed server-side by `modules/authorization/service.rs`'s `authorized_routes()` -- a fourth, independent hardcoded permission-to-route-key mapping I had not touched at all this session (distinct from the three `role_permissions`-seeding lists fixed in the prior entry). Confirmed via a direct `fetch` from the running app that `authorized_routes` genuinely had no "stock" entry even with `screen.stock` present in the raw permissions array, which fully explains why the UI still hid/blocked the route despite the account now actually holding the permission.
While auditing every other place in the backend that enumerates `screen.*` permissions (grepped for `screen.products`/`screen.reports` across `mbam-api/src`, 5 files each), found a fifth (lower-severity, not blocking, but inconsistent) location: `modules/team/service.rs`'s `dashboards_for_member()` builds a per-employee "available dashboards" list (surfaced via the team member API, likely used for an access preview UI) using the same `add_if_allowed(permission, dashboard(...))` pattern for every other screen -- also missing a `stock` entry.
Root cause: This session's original stock-permission rollout touched 3 permission-*granting* locations (`dev_seed.rs`, `team/repository.rs`, and -- after the first bug -- `dev_demo_data.rs`) but missed 2 permission-*consuming* locations that independently re-derive "which route keys does this permission set unlock" (`modules/authorization/service.rs`) or "which dashboard tiles" (`modules/team/service.rs`). Granting the raw `screen.stock` permission was necessary but not sufficient -- the route-key list the frontend actually branches on is a separate hardcoded mapping that also needed the new key added.
Files changed: `mbam-api/src/modules/authorization/service.rs` (added a `stock` entry to `authorized_routes()`, gated on `screen.stock` and `role != BaselineRole::Cashier` matching the `team` entry's convention; added two new unit tests: cashier fails closed even given the permission, shop_manager succeeds with the permission), `mbam-api/src/modules/team/service.rs` (added a matching `stock` entry to `dashboards_for_member()`, same `add_if_allowed` pattern as `products`/`team`), `mbam-api/src/checklist_tests.rs` (extended the existing `authorization_bootstrap_and_audit_events_cover_required_actions` integration test with `manager_routes.contains("stock")` and `!cashier_routes.contains("stock")` assertions, exercising the real HTTP endpoint end-to-end rather than only the new unit tests).
Verification: No Rust toolchain in this sandbox (standing constraint). Grepped every `screen.products`/`screen.reports` occurrence across all of `mbam-api/src` (5 files, both patterns) to confirm these are now the complete, exhaustive set of locations needing a "stock" counterpart, with no sixth location remaining. Re-read `AuthorizedRouteResponse`/`add_route`'s signature and `dashboard()`/`add_if_allowed`'s signature to confirm the new call sites' argument order and types match every existing sibling call exactly. Re-verified the actual symptom live against the user's running app both before this fix (confirmed via direct fetch that `authorized_routes` lacked a "stock" key despite `screen.stock` being present in `permissions`) and will re-verify again once the user rebuilds.
Errors encountered: The root-cause bug above -- a second real gap in this session's stock-permission rollout (the route-key/dashboard-tile derivation logic, not the underlying permission grant, which was already fixed correctly in the prior entry).
Checks not run: `cargo build`/`cargo test` (no Rust toolchain in this sandbox) -- asking the user to rebuild and restart mbam-api once more; the two new unit tests plus the two new integration-test assertions should all pass given the confirmed-correct existing patterns they mirror, but need the user's local `cargo test` to actually execute.
Remaining risks: Restates and sharpens the design-smell flagged in the prior entry: there are now 5 independent hardcoded per-role/per-screen lists in the backend alone (`dev_seed.rs`, `dev_demo_data.rs`, `team/repository.rs`, `modules/authorization/service.rs`, `modules/team/service.rs`) plus a 6th on the frontend (`security/accessControl.ts`'s `routeAccessByRole`/`routePermission`) and a 7th (`TeamAccessPage.tsx`'s `screenAccessOptions`) that must all independently agree for any single new screen/permission to work end-to-end. This class of bug (grant the permission, forget one of the several places that *consume* it) is very likely to recur for the next new screen unless these are consolidated into one shared source of truth -- explicitly flagging this as worth a dedicated follow-up refactor, not just noting it again.

