Change: Reorganized routing code into its own folder and authentication code into its own facade folder (both backend and frontend), gave Stock its own integrated permission scope, and let admins grant a hybrid-role user "add stock" access independently of full ledger/view access -- per the user's request to "group the source code in a way that all routing code is in a folder, authentication code in its own folder ... stock pages should have their own separate permission scope ... integrated into the current already existing permission scope ... include a way that admins can grant a user custom access to add stock in case where a user takes in a hybrid role." Clarified via AskUserQuestion: reorg covers "Both backend and frontend"; approach is a "Thin re-export layer" (facades/composition roots, no physical relocation of domain logic); the admin-grant mechanism is "Split the existing 'Stock' toggle into two" independent custom permissions.
Design note: Grepped both codebases for an existing formal `PermissionScope` abstraction first -- none exists in either; "permission scope" in this codebase just means a role's flat `permissions: string[]` array plus the several places that consume it (see the design-smell noted in the prior two entries). So "stock's own permission scope, integrated with the existing system" was interpreted as: keep stock's three permission codes (`screen.stock`, `stock.movement.view`, `stock.movement.create`) as a clean, fully-wired, self-contained group across every consuming location, rather than inventing a new abstraction the rest of the codebase doesn't have.
Backend reorg (thin facades, no logic moved): `mbam-api/src/routes/mod.rs` now also hosts `app_router(state)` -- the full CORS/tracing/`.nest(...)` composition root, moved verbatim out of `main.rs`'s old `build_router()`. `main.rs` now calls `routes::app_router(state)` and no longer builds the router itself. New `mbam-api/src/auth/` facade (`mod.rs` + `README.md`) re-exports `crate::authentication::*` at its root, `crate::security::password`/`tokens` under `auth::tokens_and_passwords`, and `crate::modules::auth::*` under `auth::handlers` -- points at the three real locations rather than moving them. `checklist_tests.rs` updated to call `routes::app_router` instead of the removed `build_router`.
Frontend reorg (thin facades, no logic moved): `App.tsx` reduced to a shell that just mounts `<BrowserRouter>` around new `routing/AppRoutes.tsx` (the full route tree, extracted verbatim with import paths shifted one level). New `routing/` folder also holds `ProtectedRoute.tsx`+`.test.tsx` (moved from `components/app/`) and `accessControl.ts`+`.test.ts` (moved from the now-deleted `security/` folder), plus a `README.md`. New `auth/index.ts` barrel re-exports the 9 auth-related service modules (`authService`, `authSessionStore`, `authSessionPersistence`, `authorizationService`, `keycloakService`, `deviceBindingService`, `offlineVaultService`, `offlineSessionService`, `offlineAuthorizationSnapshotService`) from one place, plus a `README.md`; verified no export-name collisions across the 9 files before writing it. Updated 19 import sites across the frontend from `security/accessControl` to `routing/accessControl` (services/workspaceService.ts, reports/ReportsPage.tsx+.test.tsx incl. its vi.mock string, reports/ScopedEntityReportPage.tsx+.test.tsx incl. its vi.mock string, stock/StockPage.tsx, team/TeamAccessPage.tsx, products/ProductRevenuePage.tsx, auth/AccessBootstrapPage.tsx, transactions/TransactionRecordPage.tsx+TransactionsPage.tsx, dashboard/DashboardRouter.tsx+dashboardPermissions.ts+PendingPaymentsPage.tsx+BaselineDashboards.tsx, components/app/AppShell.tsx); final grep confirmed zero remaining references to the old `security/`/`components/app/ProtectedRoute` paths.
Stock permission-scope split + hybrid-access design fix: Per the user's chosen option, split `TeamAccessPage.tsx`'s single bundled "Stock" custom-access toggle into two independent ones: `stockView` (grants `screen.stock`+`stock.movement.view`, i.e. see the ledger) and `stockCreate` (grants `stock.movement.create` alone, i.e. record movements without full ledger access) -- for a hybrid-role user who should be able to add stock but not see the whole ledger, or vice versa. Caught proactively (not user-reported): granting `stock.movement.create` alone would have been a dead-end grant with no UI path, since `/stock` was gated solely on `screen.stock` in every consuming location. Fixed by relaxing the OR-gate in all three places that decide route/dashboard access: backend `modules/authorization/service.rs`'s `authorized_routes()` (now unlocks "stock" on `screen.stock` OR `stock.movement.create`, still hard-blocked for Cashier), backend `modules/team/service.rs`'s `dashboards_for_member()` (same OR), and frontend `routing/accessControl.ts`'s `canAccessRoute` (new `routeAlternatePermission` map, checked as a fallback alongside the primary `routePermission`). `pages/stock/StockPage.tsx` itself now computes `canViewLedger`/`canCreateMovement` independently from `currentMember.permissions` and conditionally renders the record-movement form and the filter-bar/ledger table separately, instead of an all-or-nothing page. Added 2 new backend unit tests (`hybrid_role_with_only_stock_create_permission_still_reaches_the_stock_route`, `cashier_role_cannot_access_stock_via_the_create_permission_either`) and 1 new frontend test (`"unlocks the Stock route on either the screen permission or the standalone create permission"`, covering view-only/create-only/neither). Updated `i18n/cleanDashboardResources.ts`'s en/fr `stock` label to separate `stockView`/`stockCreate` labels matching the new toggle ids.
Files changed: `mbam-api/src/routes/mod.rs`, `mbam-api/src/routes/README.md`, `mbam-api/src/main.rs`, `mbam-api/src/auth/mod.rs` (new), `mbam-api/src/auth/README.md` (new), `mbam-api/src/checklist_tests.rs`, `mbam-api/src/modules/authorization/service.rs`, `mbam-api/src/modules/team/service.rs`; `mbam-web/src/App.tsx`, `mbam-web/src/routing/AppRoutes.tsx` (new), `mbam-web/src/routing/ProtectedRoute.tsx`+`.test.tsx` (moved), `mbam-web/src/routing/accessControl.ts`+`.test.ts` (moved), `mbam-web/src/routing/README.md` (new), `mbam-web/src/auth/index.ts` (new), `mbam-web/src/auth/README.md` (new), the 19 import-site files listed above, `mbam-web/src/pages/team/TeamAccessPage.tsx`, `mbam-web/src/pages/stock/StockPage.tsx`, `mbam-web/src/i18n/cleanDashboardResources.ts`; deleted `mbam-web/src/security/accessControl.ts`+`.test.ts` and `mbam-web/src/components/app/ProtectedRoute.tsx`+`.test.tsx`; `REPOSITORY_MAP.md` updated throughout (runtime-overview diagram, backend infra/domain tables, frontend UI/security tables) to reflect the new `routing/`/`auth/` folders on both sides and the split stock permission scope.
Debugging and verification performed: Frontend -- `npx tsc --noEmit` clean, `npx eslint src` clean, `npx vitest run` passed (77 tests, up from 76, across all touched/moved test files with zero broken imports), `npm run build` succeeded. Backend -- no Rust toolchain in this sandbox (standing constraint); re-read every changed file in full, reasoning through Rust module-privacy rules to confirm `auth::mod.rs`'s and `routes::mod.rs`'s facade re-exports are visible from `main.rs`/`checklist_tests.rs` (private `mod` at crate root is visible to all descendant modules of that root). Live-browser verification was performed earlier in this session (via Claude in Chrome, see the two prior entries) for the underlying stock-permission bugs this reorg builds on top of; no new live-browser pass was done for the reorg itself since it changes file organization/import wiring, not runtime permission data.
Errors encountered: None during the reorg itself -- all 19+ import-site updates resolved cleanly on the first tsc/eslint/vitest pass, and the hybrid-access gap was caught by design review before it shipped, not by a failing test.
Checks not run: `cargo check`/`cargo build`/`cargo test` (no Rust toolchain in this sandbox) -- strongly recommend the user run `cargo test` locally before treating the backend half (facade re-exports, `app_router` extraction, the two new `authorized_routes`/`dashboards_for_member` unit tests) as verified. No live-browser re-check of the reorg specifically (no runtime-visible behavior change expected from the file moves; the permission-data behavior itself was already live-verified in the two prior entries).
Remaining risks and follow-up: The underlying "5+ independent hardcoded permission lists" design smell flagged in the prior two entries is unchanged by this reorg -- it was explicitly out of scope for this request (which was about folder structure and the stock permission split, not consolidating the list-of-truth problem) and remains a candidate for a dedicated follow-up refactor. The new `auth/`/`routing/` folders are thin facades over unmoved files by deliberate choice (lower risk than physical relocation); a future session could do the heavier physical move if desired, but every import site would need re-auditing again at that point.

